1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:07,025
(Ecclesiasticus 50:10): 'Like a vessel of solid gold adorned with every precious stone

2
00:00:06,975 --> 00:00:16,812
My quotation will apply to St Augustine or to any virtuous soul, such being likened to ‘a golden vessel, massive and firm, adorned with every precious stone.

3
00:00:16,812 --> 00:00:24,950
Because of the perfection of the saints we have no likeness to express them, and we therefore symbolise them by the trees, the sun, or moon.

4
00:00:24,950 --> 00:00:31,825
So here St Augustine is compared with a chalice of gold, solid and firm, all set with precious stones.

5
00:00:31,825 --> 00:00:39,462
Indeed the same thing may be said of any saintly virtuous soul who, leaving all things here, enjoys them yonder where they are eternal.

6
00:00:39,462 --> 00:00:45,125
Whoso renounces things in their contingent sense possesses them as absolute and eternal.

7
00:00:45,125 --> 00:00:48,862
Every cup has two things: it receives and holds.

8
00:00:48,862 --> 00:00:52,025
The spiritual vessel differs from the physical.

9
00:00:52,025 --> 00:01:01,512
The wine is in the cup, not the cup in the wine, though the wine is not in the cup as it is in the body; if it were in the cup as it is in the body we should not be able to drink it.

10
00:01:01,512 --> 00:01:04,250
It is different with the spiritual vessel.

11
00:01:04,250 --> 00:01:09,312
Everything thing received in this is in the cup and the cup in it and is the cup itself.

12
00:01:09,312 --> 00:01:12,700
All this ghostly cup receives is its own nature.

13
00:01:12,700 --> 00:01:22,162
It is God’s nature to give himself to every virtuous soul, and it is the soul’s nature to receive God, and this we say referring to the soul in her loftiest capacity.

14
00:01:22,162 --> 00:01:25,600
There the soul bears the image of God and is godlike.

15
00:01:25,600 --> 00:01:30,262
No image can be without likeness, but likeness can be without image.

16
00:01:30,262 --> 00:01:40,025
Two eggs may be both alike white, but one is not the image of the other: for one to be the image of the other it must proceed out of its nature and be born of it and be like it.

17
00:01:40,025 --> 00:01:42,250
An image has two properties.

18
00:01:42,250 --> 00:01:52,812
First, it receives its being from the thing whose image it is, immediately and above will, for it is a natural product, sprouting out of its nature as a branch does out of a tree.

19
00:01:52,812 --> 00:01:57,200
Any face thrown on a mirror is, willy-nilly, imaged therein.

20
00:01:57,200 --> 00:02:05,412
But its nature does not appear in its looking-glass image: only the mouth, nose and eyes, just the features, are seen in the mirror.

21
00:02:05,412 --> 00:02:13,437
God reserves it to himself to display in his reflections, at once his nature, all he is and all he can, and this above his will.

22
00:02:13,437 --> 00:02:27,925
His image is prior to his will, will following the image, for out of his nature there leaps first his image, focussing into itself the whole promise of his nature and his essence, all his nature pouring out into his image the while it abides intact within itself.

23
00:02:27,925 --> 00:02:43,975
Now the masters locate this image not in the Holy Ghost but in the middle Person, for the Son, being the earliest issue of his nature, is therefore called his Father’s express image, and not the Holy Ghost: he is simply the flowering of the Father and the Son, and has one nature with them both.

24
00:02:43,975 --> 00:02:56,200
Will is not a mean between the nature and the image, nor, for that matter, can knowledge or perception, nay, nor wisdom, come between, for this image of God is the immediate product of his fecund nature.

25
00:02:56,200 --> 00:02:59,925
If there is means of wisdom here it is the image itself.

26
00:02:59,925 --> 00:03:03,662
Thus the Son in the Godhead is called the Wisdom of the Father.

27
00:03:03,662 --> 00:03:17,825
Know, this impartible image of God which is stamped in the soul is sealed direct in her innermost nature; this most fundamental, most noble part of her nature, is really what takes this soul-pattern, and that not by means either of will or of wisdom.

28
00:03:17,825 --> 00:03:23,875
As I remarked just now, if wisdom comes in here at all it is (as) the pattern itself.

29
00:03:23,875 --> 00:03:29,387
God exists in this image without any means and the image subsists without means in God.

30
00:03:29,387 --> 00:03:33,575
But God is much more noble in the image than the image is in God.

31
00:03:33,575 --> 00:03:42,250
The image receives God not as being the creator; it conceives him in the guise of understanding, the summit of her nature actually taking on his form.

32
00:03:42,250 --> 00:03:47,112
This is the innate divine image which God has stamped in every soul by nature.

33
00:03:47,112 --> 00:03:54,362
I durst not give more to this image: to give it more would make it God himself, which it is not, or God would not be God.

34
00:03:54,532 --> 00:03:59,269
The second characteristic of an image we note in its likeness to its object.

35
00:03:59,219 --> 00:04:02,057
And here observe especially two things.

36
00:04:02,057 --> 00:04:06,319
First: an image is not itself, neither is it its own.

37
00:04:06,319 --> 00:04:20,069
So an image received into the eye is not the eye itself nor has it any real existence in the eye but is merely suspended from and tethered to the thing it is the image of, whereto it entirely belongs and wherefrom it gets its being and is being that same being.

38
00:04:20,069 --> 00:04:22,744
Note well my definition of an image.

39
00:04:22,744 --> 00:04:27,057
There are four points to bear in mind, and haply others will occur to you.

40
00:04:27,057 --> 00:04:35,794
An image is not itself, neither is it its own: it is solely that thing’s whose reflection it is, and it is due to this alone that it exists at all.

41
00:04:35,794 --> 00:04:40,707
Things apart from the thing whose image it is, it is not and does not belong to.

42
00:04:40,707 --> 00:04:47,744
The image takes its being direct from the thing whose image it is, having one nature therewith and being the very same being.

43
00:04:47,744 --> 00:04:53,969
This is not a subject for discussion in the schools, though one may well propound it from the professorial chair.

44
00:04:53,969 --> 00:04:56,794
Ye are always asking how ye ought to live.

45
00:04:56,794 --> 00:05:03,119
Lay then to heart this answer: Just as the image is here said to do, even so it behoves thee to live.

46
00:05:03,119 --> 00:05:08,907
Be his and belonging to him, not thine own and belonging to thyself nor withal to anyone.

47
00:05:08,907 --> 00:05:15,219
Whoever has a well-beloved friend holds his belongings dear and anything against his friend he will object to.

48
00:05:15,219 --> 00:05:19,219
Take, for example, the dog, an irrational beast.

49
00:05:19,219 --> 00:05:26,569
So faithful is he to his master that he resents the things his master hates, while to his master’s friends he is most friendly.

50
00:05:26,569 --> 00:05:36,332
No count takes he of poverty or wealth; were some blind beggar his master’s bosom friend, he would be more affectionate to him than to the king or emperor who was his master’s enemy.

51
00:05:36,332 --> 00:05:42,982
I trow if it were possible the dog should be half faithless to his master, its other half were bound to hate itself.

52
00:05:42,982 --> 00:05:51,007
But then some folks complain of having no interior life, no devotion, no sweetness nor any suchlike godly consolation.

53
00:05:51,007 --> 00:05:56,357
Marry, these folk are all unrighteous still, and though they suffer it is not the best.

54
00:05:56,357 --> 00:06:06,344
Verily I say, as long as any image forms in thee which is not the eternal Word nor any shadowing forth of the eternal Word, be it never so good, in sooth it is wrong.

55
00:06:06,344 --> 00:06:17,994
That man alone is righteous who, having naughted all created things, stands facing straight along the unswerving line into the eternal Word, where, in the right, he is idealised and transformed.

56
00:06:17,994 --> 00:06:22,232
That man is gotten where the Son is gotten and is the Son himself.

57
00:06:22,232 --> 00:06:32,782
According to the scriptures, ‘No man knoweth the Father but the Son,’ and hence, if ye desire to know God, ye have to be not merely like the Son, ye have to be the very Son himself.

58
00:06:32,782 --> 00:06:39,344
Some people think to see God with their eyes as they would see a cow, and they expect to love him as they would love a cow.

59
00:06:39,344 --> 00:06:44,144
This thou lovest for its milk and for its cheese: for its profit to thyself.

60
00:06:44,144 --> 00:06:52,707
Even so do they who love God with an eye to outward riches or interior consolation, not rightly loving God but their own personal advantage.

61
00:06:52,707 --> 00:07:02,157
I trow that any object thou shalt set before thy mind, except God in himself, how good soever it may be, is nothing but a barrier to the absolute truth.

62
00:07:02,157 --> 00:07:18,969
As I said just now that St Augustine is compared to a golden cup, closed on the underside and open to the sky, even so it behoves thee to be: if thou wouldst stand with St Augustine and in the communion of saints, then close thy heart to everything created and be open to God as he is in himself.

63
00:07:18,969 --> 00:07:26,319
Men are compared with the higher faculties because they always go bareheaded, and women with the lower because the head is always veiled.

64
00:07:26,319 --> 00:07:34,819
The superior powers transcend time and space, springing straight out of the essence of the soul, and they resemble men in always going uncovered.

65
00:07:34,819 --> 00:07:37,707
Accordingly, their working is eternal.

66
00:07:37,707 --> 00:07:50,182
The philosopher says that all the powers of the soul, inasmuch as time and space affect them, have lost their virgin purity and can never be so thoroughly abstracted nor so finely sifted as to pass into the higher faculties.

67
00:07:50,182 --> 00:07:53,069
Albeit they are stamped with the same image.

68
00:07:53,236 --> 00:08:06,536
Do thou be ‘firm and steady,’ the same, that is to say, in weal and woe, in fortune and misfortune; and set with all the precious stones, a treasury, to wit, of all the virtues which come naturally pouring out of thee.

69
00:08:06,486 --> 00:08:14,061
Traverse all the virtues and, transcending them, tap virtue only at its source, where it is one with the divine nature.

70
00:08:14,061 --> 00:08:21,211
And in so far as thou art more atoned than are the angels with God’s nature, to that extent they must receive through thee.

71
00:08:21,211 --> 00:08:23,986
May we be one, So help us God.

72
00:08:23,986 --> 00:08:24,898
Amen.
